[SkillPath "practice_deals/100_miscellaneous"]
[Student "S"]
{There are three legitimate choices, 1\D, 1\S or 1NT.

You should always show a Major suit if you can, even a poor one like this.

You bid 1\S. Partner says 2\S and  

Partner has a minimum opener. You pass in a flash.

East plays 2\S. South leads the \DK.

<b>East plays 2\S. South leads the \DK.</b>

Losers: \S 3? : \H 1 : \D 2 : \C 0 : Total = 6?

Your \H loser can disappear on dummy's third \C.

If \Ss split 3-2 you can hold your losers in the suit to 3 as long as the defenders don't get a ruff. But if the defender with a doubleton trump happened to get a ruff then your trump losers would go to 4. You should lead trumps to try to prevent this.

So win the \DA and lead a \S. South will win and play 3 high \Ds. You ruff the third one in dummy. North may over-ruff, and if he does you can hope that he was the defender who started with 3 trumps. Suppose North now leads a \H. You win in your hand and play another trump, happily observing the \SK and \SA both fall. You win the rest of the tricks, discarding your \H loser on dummy's third \C.

When the defenders have a lot of high trumps you have to try to make sure they fall on the same tricks.

You were a little lucky that the defender who got the ruff, North, was the one who started with 3 trumps.}
[Play "W"]DK

